{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018Mc2X2NBcHSEuMP7MYpJ68","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Latency Model Fidelity Research: Macro-Level Implementation Plan\n     2→\n     3→> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n     4→\n     5→**Goal:** Achieve <10% BLIS E2E mean error by improving any or all of the 5 LatencyModel methods, then integrate the winner into BLIS as a third LatencyModel backend.\n     6→\n     7→**Architecture:** Python research pipeline (data loading → ideation → parallel experimentation → BLIS validation → leaderboard) with lightweight Go integration during research for BLIS validation runs, followed by production-quality Go integration.\n     8→\n     9→**Tech Stack:** Python (scikit-learn, XGBoost, pandas, scipy), Go (sim/latency/ package), BLIS calibration infrastructure (sim/workload/calibrate.go)\n    10→\n    11→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n    12→**Status:** Draft\n    13→**Based on:** [Design Document](2026-02-26-stepml-research-design.md)\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## A) Executive Summary\n    18→\n    19→The blackbox latency model uses 2 features / 3 beta coefficients for step time and returns 0 for scheduling and preemption overhead. This plan replaces it with a data-driven model covering all 5 LatencyModel methods, trained on ~165K step-level observations plus per-request lifecycle data from instrumented vLLM. The roofline model is unaffected.\n    20→\n    21→**What changes:** A new StepML LatencyModel backend joins blackbox and roofline. Ideas may improve any combination of the 5 methods — step time, queueing time, output token processing, scheduling overhead, preemption cost.\n    22→\n    23→**Primary metric:** BLIS E2E mean error < 10% per experiment, measured via BLIS simulation runs (not per-step MAPE).\n    24→\n    25→**Implementation:** 7 ordered work packages (WP0–WP6):\n    26→\n    27→- **WP0** — Shared infrastructure: data pipeline, BLIS validation harness, Go tree evaluator, blackbox E2E baseline, MFU benchmark access, per-request KV length extraction, component-level error attribution\n    28→- **WP1** — Research ideation via `/research-ideas` (3+ ideas targeting any LatencyModel methods)\n    29→- **WP2** — Hypothesis scaffolding (idea-specific sub-hypothesis decomposition — not fixed h1/h2/h3)\n    30→- **WP3** — Wave-parallel experimentation with BLIS validation runs required per idea\n    31→- **WP4** — Leaderboard comparison ranked by BLIS E2E mean error\n    32→- **WP5** — Production Go integration: StepML LatencyModel in `sim/latency/`\n    33→- **WP6** — Production BLIS validation, golden dataset update, CLAUDE.md update\n    34→\n    35→**Key constraints:** Frozen LatencyModel interface (`sim/latency_model.go:7-23`). Data integrity: train/valid/test must be strictly non-overlapping; model selection must not use BLIS E2E on training experiments. Ideas define their own splits and training strategies.\n    36→\n    37→---\n    38→\n    39→## B) Repository Recon Summary\n    40→\n    41→### B.1 Affected Packages and Files\n    42→\n    43→| Package | Files Affected | Change Type |\n    44→|---|---|---|\n    45→| `hypotheses/h-stepml/` | New directory tree | New — Python research artifacts + BLIS validation harness |\n    46→| `sim/latency/` | New `stepml.go` (lightweight in WP0, production in WP5) + modified `latency.go` factory | New + Moderate |\n    47→| `sim/` | `latency_model.go` unchanged; `config.go` minor extension | Minor — add StepML artifact path to config |\n    48→| `cmd/` | `root.go` | Minor — new CLI flag for StepML artifact path |\n    49→| `defaults.yaml` | Minor | Add StepML default config section |\n    50→| `testdata/` | `goldendataset.json` | Regenerate (WP6) |\n    51→\n    52→### B.2 Core Data Structures (Frozen — facts from merged code)\n    53→\n    54→- **LatencyModel** (`sim/latency_model.go:7-23`) — 5-method interface. Frozen.\n    55→- **NewLatencyModelFunc** (`sim/latency_model.go:31`) — Registration variable. Factory at `sim/latency/latency.go:129-167` dispatches on `hw.Roofline`.\n    56→- **Request.ProgressIndex** (`sim/request.go:34`) — `int64`, cumulative token progress. KV cache length proxy (design doc Gap 1 bridge).\n    57→- **BlackboxLatencyModel** (`sim/latency/latency.go:18-58`) — Model being replaced. `betaCoeffs[0..2]` (step time), `alphaCoeffs[0..2]` (queueing + output processing). Returns 0 for scheduling and preemption.\n    58→- **RooflineLatencyModel** (`sim/latency/latency.go:64-111`) — Unaffected. Uses `ProgressIndex` and `NumNewTokens`.\n    59→- **CalibrationReport** (`sim/workload/calibrate.go`) — `PrepareCalibrationPairs()` + `ComputeCalibration()` produce E2E/TTFT/ITL comparison metrics.\n    60→- **TraceV2 replay** (`sim/workload/replay.go`) — `LoadTraceV2Requests()` converts ground-truth traces into sim.Request for replay.\n    61→\n    62→### B.3 Call Sites (Confirmed)\n    63→\n    64→| Method | Call Site | Current Value |\n    65→|---|---|---|\n    66→| `StepTime` | `sim/simulator.go:415` | `beta0 + beta1*prefill + beta2*decode` |\n    67→| `QueueingTime` | `sim/event.go:31` | `alpha0 + alpha1*inputLen` |\n    68→| `OutputTokenProcessingTime` | `sim/simulator.go:433,437,466` | constant `alpha2` |\n    69→| `SchedulingProcessingTime` | `sim/batch_formation.go:131` | **returns 0** |\n    70→| `PreemptionProcessingTime` | `sim/batch_formation.go:160` | **returns 0** |\n    71→\n    72→### B.4 Additional Data Sources\n    73→\n    74→- **MFU benchmarks** (`InferSim/bench_data/`): Kernel-level GEMM and attention MFU data by GPU/shape/config. Available for physics-informed approaches.\n    75→- **KV events** (`kv_events.jsonl`): Block-level storage and transfer events.\n    76→- **Per-request lifecycle** (`per_request_lifecycle_metrics.json`): Per-token timestamps, input/output counts.\n    77→\n    78→---\n    79→\n    80→## C) High-Level Objectives + Non-Goals + Model Scoping\n    81→\n    82→### Objectives\n    83→\n    84→1. **Build shared infrastructure** for data loading, BLIS validation, and baseline establishment across all research ideas\n    85→2. **Build a lightweight Go tree evaluator** during Phase 0 to enable BLIS validation runs during research (not deferred to post-research)\n    86→3. **Generate 3+ research ideas** targeting any combination of the 5 LatencyModel methods — not limited to step-time-only approaches\n    87→4. **Execute parallel experiments** with idea-specific sub-hypothesis decomposition, training strategies, and data splits — subject to mandatory data integrity requirements\n    88→5. **Select a winner** achieving <10% BLIS E2E mean error, measured by BLIS simulation runs on all 16 experiments\n    89→6. **Integrate into BLIS** as a third LatencyModel implementation via the policy template extension recipe\n    90→7. **Validate in production** using BLIS calibration infrastructure on standard workload scenarios\n    91→\n    92→### Non-Goals\n    93→\n    94→- Modifying the roofline latency model — roofline must produce **byte-identical output** before and after this work\n    95→- Multi-instance cluster-level effects (latency model is instance-local)\n    96→- Non-H100 hardware training (evaluation dimension only)\n    97→- vLLM versions other than v0.15.1 (evaluation dimension only)\n    98→- Prescribing a specific training methodology or data split — ideas choose their own approach\n    99→- Automated retraining pipeline (future work)\n   100→\n   101→### Model Scoping Table\n   102→\n   103→| Component | Modeled | Simplified | Omitted | Justification |\n   104→|-----------|---------|------------|---------|---------------|\n   105→| Batch composition (prefill/decode tokens, request counts) | Yes | — | — | Direct causal inputs to step FLOPs |\n   106→| Per-request KV cache lengths | Yes (via ProgressIndex proxy + lifecycle extraction) | — | — | H8: 12.96× overestimate without per-request KV |\n   107→| All 5 LatencyModel methods | Yes (any may be improved) | — | — | E2E latency = sum of all 5 method contributions + emergent queueing |\n   108→| Model architecture (dense vs. MoE) | Yes (experiment metadata) | — | — | Fundamentally different compute patterns |\n   109→| MFU benchmarks | Yes (available from InferSim bench_data) | — | — | Enables physics-informed approaches grounding predictions in measured hardware performance |\n   110→| Hardware characteristics | — | H100-only training | — | Single GPU generation; cross-hardware is P5 |\n   111→| vLLM scheduler internals | — | Observed via batch composition + timing data | — | Scheduling/preemption overhead measurable from traces |\n   112→| Kernel-level scheduling | — | — | Yes | Below per-step abstraction; captured in target |\n   113→| Temporal dynamics | — | Independent prediction | — | Simplest approach answering AQ-1 |\n   114→| Quantization effects | — | BF16-only | — | P6 lowest priority |\n   115→\n   116→---\n   117→\n   118→## D) Concept Model\n   119→\n   120→### Building Blocks (5)\n   121→\n   122→**1. Data Pipeline** — Loads ground-truth data at multiple granularities; provides MFU benchmarks.\n   123→- OBSERVES: Raw step traces, per-request lifecycle data, KV events, InferSim bench_data MFU benchmarks\n   124→- CONTROLS: Parsed datasets at step-level, request-level, and experiment-level granularities\n   125→- OWNS: Parsed feature matrices, experiment metadata catalog\n   126→- INVARIANTS: Row counts match source; all 16 experiments present; MFU benchmarks indexed by GPU+shape\n   127→- EVENTS: None (offline)\n   128→- EXTENSION FRICTION: 1 file per new data source\n   129→\n   130→**2. BLIS Validation Harness** — Runs BLIS with candidate models on ground-truth traces; produces E2E/TTFT/ITL metrics.\n   131→- OBSERVES: Exported model artifacts (coefficients or tree JSON), ground-truth trace v2 files\n   132→- CONTROLS: Per-experiment E2E mean error, TTFT mean error, ITL mean error (the P1/P2 metrics)\n   133→- OWNS: Validation scripts, summary CSV output\n   134→- INVARIANTS: Uses existing calibrate.go infrastructure; identical metric computation as production BLIS\n   135→- EVENTS: None (offline orchestration)\n   136→- EXTENSION FRICTION: 0 files (accepts any LatencyModel via exported artifacts)\n   137→\n   138→**3. Experiment Engine** — Per-idea hypothesis chain with idea-specific decomposition.\n   139→- OBSERVES: Datasets (from Data Pipeline), BLIS metrics (from Validation Harness)\n   140→- CONTROLS: Model training, feature extraction, BLIS E2E validation, short-circuit decisions\n   141→- OWNS: Per-idea model artifacts, FINDINGS.md, idea-specific splits and training strategy\n   142→- INVARIANTS: Data integrity requirements (no leakage, non-overlapping splits); BLIS E2E reported for every idea\n   143→- EVENTS: None (offline)\n   144→- EXTENSION FRICTION: 2-3 directories per new idea\n   145→\n   146→**4. StepML LatencyModel** (Go) — Third LatencyModel behind the frozen interface.\n   147→- OBSERVES: Batch of `*Request` (InputTokens, OutputTokens, ProgressIndex, NumNewTokens)\n   148→- CONTROLS: 5 latency estimates (step time, queueing, output processing, scheduling, preemption)\n   149→- OWNS: Trained model weights/coefficients (immutable after construction)\n   150→- INVARIANTS: INV-M-1 (positive), INV-M-2 (deterministic), INV-M-3 (pure), INV-M-4 (<1ms), INV-M-5 (monotonic), INV-M-6 (|MSPE|<5%)\n   151→- EVENTS: None (synchronous query)\n   152→- EXTENSION FRICTION: ~3-4 files (impl, factory, config, CLI flag)\n   153→\n   154→**5. Leaderboard** — Cross-idea comparison ranked by BLIS E2E mean error.\n   155→- OBSERVES: All ideas' BLIS validation results and FINDINGS.md\n   156→- CONTROLS: Winner selection, final README.md\n   157→- OWNS: Leaderboard table\n   158→- INVARIANTS: Rankings use P1 (BLIS E2E) first; data integrity documented per idea\n   159→- EVENTS: None\n   160→- EXTENSION FRICTION: 1 row per new idea\n   161→\n   162→### Interaction Model\n   163→\n   164→```\n   165→[Data Pipeline] ──read-only──→ [Experiment Engine (per idea, parallel)]\n   166→                                      │\n   167→[BLIS Validation Harness] ◄──artifacts──┘\n   168→       │                              │\n   169→       └──BLIS E2E metrics──────────→ │\n   170→                                      │\n   171→[Leaderboard] ◄─────results──────────┘\n   172→       │\n   173→       ▼ (winner's artifacts)\n   174→[StepML LatencyModel (Go)]\n   175→```\n   176→\n   177→### Real-System Correspondence\n   178→\n   179→| Building Block | vLLM v0.15.1 | BLIS |\n   180→|---|---|---|\n   181→| Data Pipeline | step traces + lifecycle + KV events | `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` |\n   182→| BLIS Validation Harness | Offline comparison | `validate_blis.sh` + `sim/workload/calibrate.go` |\n   183→| StepML LatencyModel | Wall-clock model_execute() + scheduler overhead | `sim/latency/stepml.go` (new) |\n   184→\n   185→---\n   186→\n   187→## E) Architectural Risk Register\n   188→\n   189→| # | Decision | Assumption | Validation Method | Cost if Wrong | Gate |\n   190→|---|----------|------------|-------------------|---------------|------|\n   191→| R1 | ProgressIndex as KV length proxy | ProgressIndex ≈ total KV cache length per request | Compare ProgressIndex with ground-truth per-request KV from lifecycle data in WP0 | WP3–WP6 rework | Before WP3 |\n   192→| R2 | 10% sampling sufficient | Sampling is approximately random | Characterize sampling distribution in WP0 | WP3–WP4 rework | Before WP3 |\n   193→| R3 | Request-batch features suffice | Per-step prediction from Request fields achieves <10% E2E | Best model on Request-only features must pass BLIS E2E <15% on majority of experiments | WP5–WP6 rework (interface extension) | Before WP5 |\n   194→| R4 | Blackbox is beatable | Current blackbox has significant BLIS E2E error | Compute blackbox BLIS E2E baseline in WP0. If E2E mean < 12%, reassess | All WP1–WP6 wasted | Before WP1 |\n   195→| R5 | Winning model portable to Go | Model expressible as coefficients, ONNX, or compact code | Each idea documents Go integration path during WP3 | WP5 rework | Before WP5 |\n   196→| R6 | Lightweight Go evaluator is accurate | Research evaluator matches production behavior | Compare lightweight and production Go implementations on same inputs in WP5 | WP3 results invalid | Before WP5 merge |\n   197→\n   198→**Abort plans:**\n   199→- R1 fails → derive per-request KV lengths from lifecycle data instead; may need richer feature extraction\n   200→- R2 fails → request full-trace re-collection or apply importance weighting\n   201→- R3 fails → propose LatencyModel interface extension (separate design doc)\n   202→- R4 fails → cancel research; blackbox is already good enough\n   203→- R5 fails → use ONNX runtime from Go (adds dependency)\n   204→- R6 fails → rerun BLIS validation with production implementation; update leaderboard\n   205→\n   206→---\n   207→\n   208→## F) Architectural Evolution\n   209→\n   210→### Current State\n   211→\n   212→Two LatencyModel backends (`sim/latency/latency.go:129-167`):\n   213→- `hw.Roofline == true` → RooflineLatencyModel (analytical FLOPs/bandwidth)\n   214→- `hw.Roofline == false` → BlackboxLatencyModel (2-feature regression; returns 0 for scheduling/preemption)\n   215→\n   216→Factory dispatch is binary. No fallback chain. No data-driven multi-method calibration.\n   217→\n   218→### Target State\n   219→\n   220→Three LatencyModel backends with ordered dispatch:\n   221→1. `hw.Roofline == true` → RooflineLatencyModel (unchanged)\n   222→2. StepML artifact exists at configured path → StepMLLatencyModel (new — all 5 methods data-driven)\n   223→3. Fallback → BlackboxLatencyModel (preserved for backward compatibility)\n   224→\n   225→New CLI flag `--stepml-model <path>` specifies the artifact location. When absent, falls back to blackbox.\n   226→\n   227→### Evolution Path\n   228→\n   229→1. **WP0 (lightweight):** Add `sim/latency/stepml.go` with minimal tree evaluator + coefficient loader. Registers via existing factory. Enables BLIS validation during research. Not production quality.\n   230→2. **WP5 (production):** Replace lightweight implementation with production-quality code — proper error handling, comprehensive tests (INV-M-1 through INV-M-6), R20 degenerate input handling.\n   231→\n   232→### What Remains Unchanged\n   233→\n   234→- LatencyModel interface (frozen at `sim/latency_model.go:7-23`)\n   235→- **RooflineLatencyModel: zero code changes.** The `--roofline` path returns before StepML dispatch.\n   236→- All call sites (`sim/simulator.go`, `sim/event.go`, `sim/batch_formation.go`)\n   237→- Batch formation, scheduling, routing, KV cache modules\n   238→- Cluster-level configuration\n   239→\n   240→### Roofline Isolation Guarantee\n   241→\n   242→StepML findings for scheduling overhead, preemption, and queueing apply ONLY to the StepML LatencyModel. Not propagated to roofline because:\n   243→1. Factory dispatch order: `hw.Roofline == true` checked first — StepML unreachable when roofline active\n   244→2. No shared mutable state: separate artifacts and coefficients\n   245→3. No defaults.yaml changes for roofline\n   246→4. Verification: regression test asserting byte-identical `--roofline` stdout (INV-6)\n   247→\n   248→---\n   249→\n   250→## G) Frozen Interface Reference\n   251→\n   252→```go\n   253→// sim/latency_model.go:7-23\n   254→type LatencyModel interface {\n   255→    StepTime(batch []*Request) int64\n   256→    QueueingTime(req *Request) int64\n   257→    OutputTokenProcessingTime() int64\n   258→    SchedulingProcessingTime() int64\n   259→    PreemptionProcessingTime() int64\n   260→}\n   261→```\n   262→\n   263→Registration variable (`sim/latency_model.go:31`):\n   264→```go\n   265→var NewLatencyModelFunc func(coeffs LatencyCoeffs, hw ModelHardwareConfig) (LatencyModel, error)\n   266→```\n   267→\n   268→Factory (`sim/latency/latency.go:129`):\n   269→```go\n   270→func NewLatencyModel(coeffs sim.LatencyCoeffs, hw sim.ModelHardwareConfig) (sim.LatencyModel, error)\n   271→```\n   272→\n   273→---\n   274→\n   275→## H) Cross-Cutting Infrastructure Plan\n   276→\n   277→### H.1 Shared Test Infrastructure\n   278→\n   279→- **Existing:** `hypotheses/lib/harness.sh`, `hypotheses/lib/analyze_helpers.py`\n   280→- **New (WP0):** `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` — data loader, evaluation harness, BLIS validation harness, baselines, feature extraction tools. All ideas use these.\n   281→- **New (WP0):** `sim/latency/stepml.go` — lightweight Go tree evaluator for BLIS validation during research\n   282→- **New (WP5):** `sim/latency/stepml_test.go` — production Go unit tests with INV-M-1 through INV-M-6\n   283→\n   284→### H.2 Documentation Maintenance\n   285→\n   286→| Trigger | Owner | What Updates |\n   287→|---|---|---|\n   288→| WP0 creates `hypotheses/h-stepml/` and `sim/latency/stepml.go` | WP0 | CLAUDE.md file organization + latency estimation section |\n   289→| WP0 adds `--stepml-model` flag | WP0 | CLAUDE.md CLI flags |\n   290→| WP5 replaces lightweight with production implementation | WP5 | CLAUDE.md latency estimation section |\n   291→| WP6 regenerates golden dataset | WP6 | CLAUDE.md golden dataset note |\n   292→\n   293→### H.3 CI Pipeline Changes\n   294→\n   295→- **WP0:** New Go file added to `go test ./sim/latency/...`. Lightweight tests only.\n   296→- **WP0–WP4:** Python research code not CI-gated; reproducibility via run.sh\n   297→- **WP5:** Production Go tests + benchmarks\n   298→- **WP6:** Golden dataset regeneration + `go test ./...` verification\n   299→\n   300→### H.4 Dependency Management\n   301→\n   302→- **Python (WP0–WP4):** `requirements.txt` in `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` with pinned versions\n   303→- **Go (WP0):** Zero new dependencies for lightweight evaluator (pure Go tree traversal + JSON parsing)\n   304→- **Go (WP5):** Depends on winning model. Coefficient export = zero new deps. ONNX = adds `onnxruntime-go`.\n   305→\n   306→### H.5 Interface Freeze Schedule\n   307→\n   308→- **LatencyModel interface:** Already frozen. No changes.\n   309→- **NewLatencyModelFunc signature:** Already frozen. StepML uses existing `ModelHardwareConfig` with optional new fields.\n   310→- **No new interfaces introduced.** StepML is a policy template.\n   311→\n   312→---\n   313→\n   314→## I) Work Package Plan\n   315→\n   316→### WP0: Shared Infrastructure + BLIS Validation Loop\n   317→\n   318→**Building Block Change:** Adds Data Pipeline + BLIS Validation Harness + lightweight StepML LatencyModel\n   319→**Extension Type:** Subsystem module (new infrastructure) + policy template (lightweight Go evaluator)\n   320→**Motivation:** All subsequent WPs depend on data loading, BLIS validation capability, and the blackbox E2E baseline. The BLIS validation harness is the primary evaluation tool — without it, ideas cannot measure the P1 metric.\n   321→\n   322→**Scope:**\n   323→- In: Data parsing (step-level + request-level + MFU benchmarks from InferSim bench_data), Python evaluation harness, Go tree evaluator, BLIS validation harness, blackbox E2E baseline, component-level error attribution, per-request KV length extraction, sampling bias characterization, prefix cache semantics (D-8)\n   324→- Out: Any model training, any idea-specific code, production-quality Go implementation\n   325→\n   326→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   327→- BC-0-1: Row count of parsed datasets matches source file counts\n   328→- BC-0-2: MFU benchmark data indexed and queryable by GPU type, matrix shape, attention config\n   329→- BC-0-3: Go tree evaluator implements all 5 LatencyModel methods and loads exported artifacts\n   330→- BC-0-4: BLIS validation harness runs all 16 experiments and outputs E2E/TTFT/ITL mean errors\n   331→- BC-0-5: Blackbox E2E baseline established (the number Round 2 must beat)\n   332→- BC-0-6: Component-level error attribution identifies which of the 5 methods dominates E2E error\n   333→- BC-0-7: Sampling bias report documents step_id uniformity, autocorrelation, per-experiment representation\n   334→\n   335→**Risks:**\n   336→1. Sampling is systematically biased → characterization detects it; abort per R2\n   337→2. Blackbox already achieves <12% E2E mean → reassess research justification per R4\n   338→3. Go tree evaluator has accuracy issues → validated against Python predictions before WP3\n   339→\n   340→**Cross-Cutting:** Creates `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` and `sim/latency/stepml.go`. Updates CLAUDE.md.\n   341→\n   342→**Validation Gate:** R1, R2, R4 must pass before WP1.\n   343→\n   344→---\n   345→\n   346→**Implementation Guide:**\n   347→\n   348→**Architectural Impact:** Adds `sim/latency/stepml.go` as a third LatencyModel backend (lightweight, research-only). Adds Python infrastructure under `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/`.\n   349→\n   350→**Tasks (grouped by subsystem):**\n   351→\n   352→*Data loading and characterization:*\n   353→1. Create directory structure and requirements.txt\n   354→2. Implement data loader: parse step-level traces from all 20 experiments into unified Parquet\n   355→3. Implement request-level data loader: parse per-request lifecycle metrics\n   356→4. Index MFU benchmarks from InferSim bench_data (make queryable by GPU+shape+config)\n   357→5. Characterize sampling distribution (bias detection per R2 gate)\n   358→6. Verify step.duration_us semantics + resolve prefix cache semantics (D-8)\n   359→\n   360→*Python evaluation (diagnostics):*\n   361→7. Implement per-step evaluation harness (MAPE, MSPE, Pearson r, p99 error, bootstrap CI)\n   362→8. Implement per-step baselines (blackbox re-trained, roofline, naive mean)\n   363→\n   364→*Feature extraction tools:*\n   365→9. Component-level error attribution tool (e2e_decomposition.py): ablate each of 5 methods to measure marginal E2E error contribution\n   366→10. Per-request KV length extractor (lifecycle_kv_extractor.py): derive per-step kv_mean, kv_max, kv_sum from lifecycle data\n   367→\n   368→*BLIS validation infrastructure:*\n   369→11. Go tree evaluator (sim/latency/stepml.go): lightweight LatencyModel loading exported artifacts, ~200 lines\n   370→12. BLIS validation harness (validate_blis.sh): run BLIS on 16 traces, output E2E/TTFT/ITL per experiment\n   371→13. Blackbox E2E baseline: run validation harness with current blackbox coefficients — establish the baseline\n   372→14. Validate ProgressIndex as KV proxy (R1 gate)\n   373→\n   374→---\n   375→\n   376→### WP1: Research Ideation\n   377→\n   378→**Building Block Change:** Populates Experiment Engine inputs\n   379→**Extension Type:** Process (skill invocation)\n   380→**Motivation:** Generate 3+ literature-grounded ideas for achieving <10% BLIS E2E mean error via any combination of LatencyModel method improvements.\n   381→\n   382→**Scope:**\n   383→- In: Write `problem.md` from design doc (including WP0 baseline results + component error attribution), invoke `/research-ideas`\n   384→- Out: Model training, experiment execution\n   385→\n   386→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   387→- BC-1-1: `research.md` contains 3+ ideas with literature citations\n   388→- BC-1-2: Each idea specifies which of the 5 LatencyModel methods it targets\n   389→- BC-1-3: Each idea documents its Go integration path\n   390→- BC-1-4: Ideas are diverse — not all limited to step-time-only ML models\n   391→\n   392→**Risks:**\n   393→1. Ideas are too similar → problem.md explicitly requests diverse approaches (e.g., step-time ML, end-to-end calibration, multi-component optimization)\n   394→2. Ideas ignore the non-StepTime methods → problem.md includes WP0 component error attribution showing which methods contribute most to E2E error\n   395→\n   396→**Cross-Cutting:** None. Produces `research.md` consumed by WP2.\n   397→\n   398→---\n   399→\n   400→### WP2: Hypothesis Scaffolding\n   401→\n   402→**Building Block Change:** Adds Experiment Engine structure\n   403→**Extension Type:** Process (directory creation + HYPOTHESIS.md authoring)\n   404→**Motivation:** Map research ideas to testable hypotheses with idea-specific sub-hypothesis decomposition.\n   405→\n   406→**Scope:**\n   407→- In: Extract top 3-5 ideas from research.md, create per-idea directories, write HYPOTHESIS.md files\n   408→- Out: Experiment code, running experiments\n   409→\n   410→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   411→- BC-2-1: Each idea has 2-3 sub-hypotheses with idea-specific decomposition (NOT fixed h1-features/h2-model/h3-generalization)\n   412→- BC-2-2: Each HYPOTHESIS.md includes Related Work with citations from research.md\n   413→- BC-2-3: At least one sub-hypothesis per idea reports BLIS E2E mean error\n   414→- BC-2-4: Claims and refutation criteria expressed in terms of BLIS E2E mean error where possible\n   415→- BC-2-5: Each idea documents its training strategy and data split approach (subject to data integrity requirements)\n   416→\n   417→**Risks:**\n   418→1. Ideas don't map to hypotheses → each idea must specify a falsifiable BLIS E2E claim\n   419→\n   420→**Cross-Cutting:** Creates directory structure consumed by WP3.\n   421→\n   422→**Validation Gate:** Convergence review (h-design, 5 perspectives) on each idea's HYPOTHESIS.md.\n   423→\n   424→---\n   425→\n   426→### WP3: Wave-Parallel Experimentation\n   427→\n   428→**Building Block Change:** Executes Experiment Engine\n   429→**Extension Type:** Policy template (new algorithms per idea)\n   430→**Motivation:** Test each idea's approach and measure BLIS E2E mean error.\n   431→\n   432→**Scope:**\n   433→- In: All sub-hypotheses per idea, using WP0 shared infrastructure\n   434→- Out: Production Go integration (that's WP5)\n   435→\n   436→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   437→- BC-3-1: Every idea uses WP0's data loader (no custom parsing)\n   438→- BC-3-2: Every idea's final sub-hypothesis reports BLIS E2E mean error via validate_blis.sh\n   439→- BC-3-3: Every FINDINGS.md includes BLIS E2E per experiment + data integrity documentation (which data was training vs. evaluation)\n   440→- BC-3-4: Data integrity requirements satisfied: non-overlapping splits, no feature leakage, no model selection on training experiments' BLIS E2E\n   441→- BC-3-5: Ideas with BLIS E2E worse than blackbox baseline are dropped\n   442→- BC-3-6: Each idea's training strategy and split documented and justified\n   443→\n   444→**Risks:**\n   445→1. All ideas fail → re-examine feature assumptions; revisit R1, R3\n   446→2. BLIS validation harness bottleneck → each BLIS run takes ~2-5 min; 16 experiments × multiple ideas is manageable\n   447→\n   448→**Cross-Cutting:** Consumes WP0 shared infrastructure. Each idea writes only to its own directory.\n   449→\n   450→**Validation Gate:** R3 evaluated after WP3. R5 confirmed for surviving ideas.\n   451→\n   452→---\n   453→\n   454→### WP4: Leaderboard & Selection\n   455→\n   456→**Building Block Change:** Populates Leaderboard\n   457→**Extension Type:** Process (analysis + documentation)\n   458→**Motivation:** Compare all ideas on BLIS E2E mean error and select the winner.\n   459→\n   460→**Scope:**\n   461→- In: All ideas' BLIS validation results and FINDINGS.md\n   462→- Out: Winner selection, README.md with leaderboard\n   463→\n   464→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   465→- BC-4-1: Rankings ordered by P1 metric (BLIS E2E mean error) first\n   466→- BC-4-2: Data integrity verified: each idea's training/evaluation boundary documented\n   467→- BC-4-3: Winner identified with Go integration path documented\n   468→- BC-4-4: Falsification criteria checked (design doc section)\n   469→\n   470→**Risks:**\n   471→1. No idea achieves <10% BLIS E2E → evaluate falsification criteria; consider abandoning StepML\n   472→\n   473→**Cross-Cutting:** Produces README.md. Inputs to WP5.\n   474→\n   475→---\n   476→\n   477→### WP5: Production Go Integration\n   478→\n   479→**Building Block Change:** Replaces lightweight StepML with production implementation\n   480→**Extension Type:** Policy template (production-quality algorithm behind LatencyModel interface)\n   481→**Motivation:** Replace WP0's lightweight Go evaluator with production-quality code.\n   482→\n   483→**Scope:**\n   484→- In: Winning model's artifacts and integration path from WP4\n   485→- Out: Production BLIS validation (that's WP6)\n   486→\n   487→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   488→- BC-5-1: StepML implements all 5 LatencyModel methods (production quality)\n   489→- BC-5-2: Factory dispatch: roofline → stepml (if artifact) → blackbox (fallback)\n   490→- BC-5-3: INV-M-1 through INV-M-6 all pass with comprehensive tests\n   491→- BC-5-4: All existing tests pass (roofline and blackbox unchanged)\n   492→- BC-5-5: CLI flag validated per R3/R10/R18\n   493→- BC-5-6: Roofline isolation regression test — byte-identical stdout (INV-6)\n   494→- BC-5-7: R20 degenerate inputs handled (all cases from design doc table)\n   495→- BC-5-8: Production predictions match lightweight evaluator results on same inputs (R6 validation)\n   496→\n   497→**Risks:**\n   498→1. Model too complex for Go → ONNX runtime or coefficient export\n   499→2. Prediction latency > 1ms → simplify or approximate\n   500→\n   501→**Cross-Cutting:** Updates CLAUDE.md. Creates production `sim/latency/stepml.go` and `sim/latency/stepml_test.go`.\n   502→\n   503→---\n   504→\n   505→### WP6: Production Validation & Promotion\n   506→\n   507→**Building Block Change:** Validates StepML end-to-end; promotes to default\n   508→**Extension Type:** Tier composition (validation over existing simulation)\n   509→**Motivation:** Verify production Go implementation matches research results and passes Stage 2 integration gate.\n   510→\n   511→**Scope:**\n   512→- In: Production StepML from WP5, standard workload scenarios\n   513→- Out: Updated golden dataset, CLAUDE.md\n   514→\n   515→**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n   516→- BC-6-1: BLIS E2E mean error < 10% on standard workloads (production Go, not lightweight evaluator)\n   517→- BC-6-2: TTFT mean error < 15%, ITL mean error < 15%\n   518→- BC-6-3: No P99 ranking inversions vs. blackbox\n   519→- BC-6-4: Throughput prediction error < 15%\n   520→- BC-6-5: Golden dataset regenerated and documented (R12)\n   521→- BC-6-6: INV-6 determinism: two runs with same seed produce byte-identical stdout\n   522→\n   523→**Risks:**\n   524→1. Production implementation diverges from lightweight evaluator → R6 gate catches this\n   525→2. Golden dataset changes break tests → regenerate with verification\n   526→\n   527→**Cross-Cutting:** Updates CLAUDE.md (defaults, implementation focus). Regenerates `testdata/goldendataset.json`.\n   528→\n   529→---\n   530→\n   531→## J) Dependency DAG\n   532→\n   533→```\n   534→WP0 (Shared Infrastructure + BLIS Validation Loop + Go Evaluator)\n   535→ │\n   536→ ├── R1, R2, R4 validation gates\n   537→ │\n   538→ ▼\n   539→WP1 (Research Ideation)\n   540→ │\n   541→ ▼\n   542→WP2 (Hypothesis Scaffolding)\n   543→ │\n   544→ ├─────────┬─────────┐\n   545→ ▼         ▼         ▼\n   546→WP3-a    WP3-b    WP3-c    (parallel across ideas; sequential sub-hypotheses within)\n   547→ │         │         │\n   548→ └─────────┴─────────┘\n   549→           │\n   550→           ├── R3, R5 validation gates\n   551→           ▼\n   552→         WP4 (Leaderboard — ranked by BLIS E2E)\n   553→           │\n   554→           ▼\n   555→         WP5 (Production Go Integration)\n   556→           │\n   557→           ├── R6 validation gate\n   558→           ▼\n   559→         WP6 (Production Validation & Promotion)\n   560→```\n   561→\n   562→**Parallelizable workstreams:**\n   563→- WP3-a, WP3-b, WP3-c are fully parallel (independent ideas, shared read-only data)\n   564→- Within WP3-x: sub-hypotheses are sequential (idea-specific dependency chain)\n   565→- WP5 and WP6 are strictly sequential\n   566→\n   567→**Merge sequencing:**\n   568→- WP0 must complete and pass R1/R2/R4 before WP1\n   569→- WP2 must complete before any WP3\n   570→- All WP3 must complete before WP4\n   571→- WP4 must confirm R3/R5 before WP5\n   572→- WP5 must pass R6 before WP6\n   573→\n   574→---\n   575→\n   576→## K) Design Bug Prevention Checklist\n   577→\n   578→### General\n   579→\n   580→- [ ] **Scaffolding creep:** Every Python module in WP0 has tests. Go evaluator in WP0 has basic tests. No dead code.\n   581→- [ ] **Documentation drift:** CLAUDE.md updated in WP0 (Go evaluator, shared infra), WP5 (production), WP6 (golden dataset).\n   582→- [ ] **Test infrastructure duplication:** All experiments use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` and `validate_blis.sh`.\n   583→- [ ] **Golden dataset staleness:** WP6 regenerates with verification (R12).\n   584→\n   585→### DES-Specific\n   586→\n   587→- [ ] **Type catalog trap:** No Go struct definitions in this macro plan. Evolution described behaviorally.\n   588→- [ ] **Fidelity for its own sake:** Every modeled component traces to AQ-1 (E2E mean fidelity).\n   589→- [ ] **Golden without invariant:** WP5 includes INV-M-1 through INV-M-6 companion tests.\n   590→- [ ] **Mixing exogenous and endogenous:** StepML is a pure query (no events, no state mutation).\n   591→\n   592→### Module Architecture\n   593→\n   594→- [ ] **Shotgun surgery:** StepML constructed in one place (factory in `sim/latency/latency.go`).\n   595→- [ ] **Config mixing:** StepML config fields module-scoped (R16).\n   596→- [ ] **No silent data loss (R1):** Factory fallback logged, not silent.\n   597→- [ ] **Guard division (R11):** Zero denominators checked in prediction code.\n   598→- [ ] **Strict YAML parsing (R10):** New fields use `yaml.KnownFields(true)`.\n   599→- [ ] **CLI flag precedence (R18):** `--stepml-model` does not silently override defaults.yaml.\n   600→\n   601→### Roofline Isolation\n   602→\n   603→- [ ] **Roofline byte-identical output:** WP5 regression test (BC-5-6).\n   604→- [ ] **No roofline code touched:** StepML branch after `if hw.Roofline` check.\n   605→- [ ] **No alpha coefficient sharing:** Separate artifacts.\n   606→- [ ] **No defaults.yaml roofline changes:** Additive StepML section only.\n   607→\n   608→### Data Integrity (Research-Specific)\n   609→\n   610→- [ ] **No data leakage:** Every idea's train/valid/test sets are strictly non-overlapping (Integrity Req #1).\n   611→- [ ] **No evaluation on training data:** Metrics clearly labeled as training vs. validation (Integrity Req #2).\n   612→- [ ] **BLIS E2E boundary:** Model selection/tuning not done on BLIS E2E of training experiments (Integrity Req #3).\n   613→- [ ] **Temporal leakage awareness:** Ideas using step-level splits document their leakage prevention (Integrity Req #4).\n   614→- [ ] **Feature leakage:** No post-execution features used as inputs (Integrity Req #5).\n   615→- [ ] **Reproducibility:** Seeds fixed, splits saved, dependencies pinned (Integrity Req #6).\n   616→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c72182bb-90d4-4f72-be1e-6f3d8138bce2","uuid":"879088cb-a93a-44b4-ae11-02feafc31380","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-1-constrained-cmaes/docs/plans/2026-02-26-stepml-research-macro-plan.md","content":"# Latency Model Fidelity Research: Macro-Level Implementation Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n\n**Goal:** Achieve <10% BLIS E2E mean error by improving any or all of the 5 LatencyModel methods, then integrate the winner into BLIS as a third LatencyModel backend.\n\n**Architecture:** Python research pipeline (data loading → ideation → parallel experimentation → BLIS validation → leaderboard) with lightweight Go integration during research for BLIS validation runs, followed by production-quality Go integration.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Python (scikit-learn, XGBoost, pandas, scipy), Go (sim/latency/ package), BLIS calibration infrastructure (sim/workload/calibrate.go)\n\n**Date:** 2026-02-26\n**Status:** Draft\n**Based on:** [Design Document](2026-02-26-stepml-research-design.md)\n\n---\n\n## A) Executive Summary\n\nThe blackbox latency model uses 2 features / 3 beta coefficients for step time and returns 0 for scheduling and preemption overhead. This plan replaces it with a data-driven model covering all 5 LatencyModel methods, trained on ~165K step-level observations plus per-request lifecycle data from instrumented vLLM. The roofline model is unaffected.\n\n**What changes:** A new StepML LatencyModel backend joins blackbox and roofline. Ideas may improve any combination of the 5 methods — step time, queueing time, output token processing, scheduling overhead, preemption cost.\n\n**Primary metric:** BLIS E2E mean error < 10% per experiment, measured via BLIS simulation runs (not per-step MAPE).\n\n**Implementation:** 7 ordered work packages (WP0–WP6):\n\n- **WP0** — Shared infrastructure: data pipeline, BLIS validation harness, Go tree evaluator, blackbox E2E baseline, MFU benchmark access, per-request KV length extraction, component-level error attribution\n- **WP1** — Research ideation via `/research-ideas` (3+ ideas targeting any LatencyModel methods)\n- **WP2** — Hypothesis scaffolding (idea-specific sub-hypothesis decomposition — not fixed h1/h2/h3)\n- **WP3** — Wave-parallel experimentation with BLIS validation runs required per idea\n- **WP4** — Leaderboard comparison ranked by BLIS E2E mean error\n- **WP5** — Production Go integration: StepML LatencyModel in `sim/latency/`\n- **WP6** — Production BLIS validation, golden dataset update, CLAUDE.md update\n\n**Key constraints:** Frozen LatencyModel interface (`sim/latency_model.go:7-23`). Data integrity: train/valid/test must be strictly non-overlapping; model selection must not use BLIS E2E on training experiments. Ideas define their own splits and training strategies.\n\n---\n\n## B) Repository Recon Summary\n\n### B.1 Affected Packages and Files\n\n| Package | Files Affected | Change Type |\n|---|---|---|\n| `hypotheses/h-stepml/` | New directory tree | New — Python research artifacts + BLIS validation harness |\n| `sim/latency/` | New `stepml.go` (lightweight in WP0, production in WP5) + modified `latency.go` factory | New + Moderate |\n| `sim/` | `latency_model.go` unchanged; `config.go` minor extension | Minor — add StepML artifact path to config |\n| `cmd/` | `root.go` | Minor — new CLI flag for StepML artifact path |\n| `defaults.yaml` | Minor | Add StepML default config section |\n| `testdata/` | `goldendataset.json` | Regenerate (WP6) |\n\n### B.2 Core Data Structures (Frozen — facts from merged code)\n\n- **LatencyModel** (`sim/latency_model.go:7-23`) — 5-method interface. Frozen.\n- **NewLatencyModelFunc** (`sim/latency_model.go:31`) — Registration variable. Factory at `sim/latency/latency.go:129-167` dispatches on `hw.Roofline`.\n- **Request.ProgressIndex** (`sim/request.go:34`) — `int64`, cumulative token progress. KV cache length proxy (design doc Gap 1 bridge).\n- **BlackboxLatencyModel** (`sim/latency/latency.go:18-58`) — Model being replaced. `betaCoeffs[0..2]` (step time), `alphaCoeffs[0..2]` (queueing + output processing). Returns 0 for scheduling and preemption.\n- **RooflineLatencyModel** (`sim/latency/latency.go:64-111`) — Unaffected. Uses `ProgressIndex` and `NumNewTokens`.\n- **CalibrationReport** (`sim/workload/calibrate.go`) — `PrepareCalibrationPairs()` + `ComputeCalibration()` produce E2E/TTFT/ITL comparison metrics.\n- **TraceV2 replay** (`sim/workload/replay.go`) — `LoadTraceV2Requests()` converts ground-truth traces into sim.Request for replay.\n\n### B.3 Call Sites (Confirmed)\n\n| Method | Call Site | Current Value |\n|---|---|---|\n| `StepTime` | `sim/simulator.go:415` | `beta0 + beta1*prefill + beta2*decode` |\n| `QueueingTime` | `sim/event.go:31` | `alpha0 + alpha1*inputLen` |\n| `OutputTokenProcessingTime` | `sim/simulator.go:433,437,466` | constant `alpha2` |\n| `SchedulingProcessingTime` | `sim/batch_formation.go:131` | **returns 0** |\n| `PreemptionProcessingTime` | `sim/batch_formation.go:160` | **returns 0** |\n\n### B.4 Additional Data Sources\n\n- **MFU benchmarks** (`InferSim/bench_data/`): Kernel-level GEMM and attention MFU data by GPU/shape/config. Available for physics-informed approaches.\n- **KV events** (`kv_events.jsonl`): Block-level storage and transfer events.\n- **Per-request lifecycle** (`per_request_lifecycle_metrics.json`): Per-token timestamps, input/output counts.\n\n---\n\n## C) High-Level Objectives + Non-Goals + Model Scoping\n\n### Objectives\n\n1. **Build shared infrastructure** for data loading, BLIS validation, and baseline establishment across all research ideas\n2. **Build a lightweight Go tree evaluator** during Phase 0 to enable BLIS validation runs during research (not deferred to post-research)\n3. **Generate 3+ research ideas** targeting any combination of the 5 LatencyModel methods — not limited to step-time-only approaches\n4. **Execute parallel experiments** with idea-specific sub-hypothesis decomposition, training strategies, and data splits — subject to mandatory data integrity requirements\n5. **Select a winner** achieving <10% BLIS E2E mean error, measured by BLIS simulation runs on all 16 experiments\n6. **Integrate into BLIS** as a third LatencyModel implementation via the policy template extension recipe\n7. **Validate in production** using BLIS calibration infrastructure on standard workload scenarios\n\n### Non-Goals\n\n- Modifying the roofline latency model — roofline must produce **byte-identical output** before and after this work\n- Multi-instance cluster-level effects (latency model is instance-local)\n- Non-H100 hardware training (evaluation dimension only)\n- vLLM versions other than v0.15.1 (evaluation dimension only)\n- Prescribing a specific training methodology or data split — ideas choose their own approach\n- Automated retraining pipeline (future work)\n\n### Model Scoping Table\n\n| Component | Modeled | Simplified | Omitted | Justification |\n|-----------|---------|------------|---------|---------------|\n| Batch composition (prefill/decode tokens, request counts) | Yes | — | — | Direct causal inputs to step FLOPs |\n| Per-request KV cache lengths | Yes (via ProgressIndex proxy + lifecycle extraction) | — | — | H8: 12.96× overestimate without per-request KV |\n| All 5 LatencyModel methods | Yes (any may be improved) | — | — | E2E latency = sum of all 5 method contributions + emergent queueing |\n| Model architecture (dense vs. MoE) | Yes (experiment metadata) | — | — | Fundamentally different compute patterns |\n| MFU benchmarks | Yes (available from InferSim bench_data) | — | — | Enables physics-informed approaches grounding predictions in measured hardware performance |\n| Hardware characteristics | — | H100-only training | — | Single GPU generation; cross-hardware is P5 |\n| vLLM scheduler internals | — | Observed via batch composition + timing data | — | Scheduling/preemption overhead measurable from traces |\n| Kernel-level scheduling | — | — | Yes | Below per-step abstraction; captured in target |\n| Temporal dynamics | — | Independent prediction | — | Simplest approach answering AQ-1 |\n| Quantization effects | — | BF16-only | — | P6 lowest priority |\n\n---\n\n## D) Concept Model\n\n### Building Blocks (5)\n\n**1. Data Pipeline** — Loads ground-truth data at multiple granularities; provides MFU benchmarks.\n- OBSERVES: Raw step traces, per-request lifecycle data, KV events, InferSim bench_data MFU benchmarks\n- CONTROLS: Parsed datasets at step-level, request-level, and experiment-level granularities\n- OWNS: Parsed feature matrices, experiment metadata catalog\n- INVARIANTS: Row counts match source; all 16 experiments present; MFU benchmarks indexed by GPU+shape\n- EVENTS: None (offline)\n- EXTENSION FRICTION: 1 file per new data source\n\n**2. BLIS Validation Harness** — Runs BLIS with candidate models on ground-truth traces; produces E2E/TTFT/ITL metrics.\n- OBSERVES: Exported model artifacts (coefficients or tree JSON), ground-truth trace v2 files\n- CONTROLS: Per-experiment E2E mean error, TTFT mean error, ITL mean error (the P1/P2 metrics)\n- OWNS: Validation scripts, summary CSV output\n- INVARIANTS: Uses existing calibrate.go infrastructure; identical metric computation as production BLIS\n- EVENTS: None (offline orchestration)\n- EXTENSION FRICTION: 0 files (accepts any LatencyModel via exported artifacts)\n\n**3. Experiment Engine** — Per-idea hypothesis chain with idea-specific decomposition.\n- OBSERVES: Datasets (from Data Pipeline), BLIS metrics (from Validation Harness)\n- CONTROLS: Model training, feature extraction, BLIS E2E validation, short-circuit decisions\n- OWNS: Per-idea model artifacts, FINDINGS.md, idea-specific splits and training strategy\n- INVARIANTS: Data integrity requirements (no leakage, non-overlapping splits); BLIS E2E reported for every idea\n- EVENTS: None (offline)\n- EXTENSION FRICTION: 2-3 directories per new idea\n\n**4. StepML LatencyModel** (Go) — Third LatencyModel behind the frozen interface.\n- OBSERVES: Batch of `*Request` (InputTokens, OutputTokens, ProgressIndex, NumNewTokens)\n- CONTROLS: 5 latency estimates (step time, queueing, output processing, scheduling, preemption)\n- OWNS: Trained model weights/coefficients (immutable after construction)\n- INVARIANTS: INV-M-1 (positive), INV-M-2 (deterministic), INV-M-3 (pure), INV-M-4 (<1ms), INV-M-5 (monotonic), INV-M-6 (|MSPE|<5%)\n- EVENTS: None (synchronous query)\n- EXTENSION FRICTION: ~3-4 files (impl, factory, config, CLI flag)\n\n**5. Leaderboard** — Cross-idea comparison ranked by BLIS E2E mean error.\n- OBSERVES: All ideas' BLIS validation results and FINDINGS.md\n- CONTROLS: Winner selection, final README.md\n- OWNS: Leaderboard table\n- INVARIANTS: Rankings use P1 (BLIS E2E) first; data integrity documented per idea\n- EVENTS: None\n- EXTENSION FRICTION: 1 row per new idea\n\n### Interaction Model\n\n```\n[Data Pipeline] ──read-only──→ [Experiment Engine (per idea, parallel)]\n                                      │\n[BLIS Validation Harness] ◄──artifacts──┘\n       │                              │\n       └──BLIS E2E metrics──────────→ │\n                                      │\n[Leaderboard] ◄─────results──────────┘\n       │\n       ▼ (winner's artifacts)\n[StepML LatencyModel (Go)]\n```\n\n### Real-System Correspondence\n\n| Building Block | vLLM v0.15.1 | BLIS |\n|---|---|---|\n| Data Pipeline | step traces + lifecycle + KV events | `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` |\n| BLIS Validation Harness | Offline comparison | `validate_blis.sh` + `sim/workload/calibrate.go` |\n| StepML LatencyModel | Wall-clock model_execute() + scheduler overhead | `sim/latency/stepml.go` (new) |\n\n---\n\n## E) Architectural Risk Register\n\n| # | Decision | Assumption | Validation Method | Cost if Wrong | Gate |\n|---|----------|------------|-------------------|---------------|------|\n| R1 | ProgressIndex as KV length proxy | ProgressIndex ≈ total KV cache length per request | Compare ProgressIndex with ground-truth per-request KV from lifecycle data in WP0 | WP3–WP6 rework | Before WP3 |\n| R2 | 10% sampling sufficient | Sampling is approximately random | Characterize sampling distribution in WP0 | WP3–WP4 rework | Before WP3 |\n| R3 | Request-batch features suffice | Per-step prediction from Request fields achieves <10% E2E | Best model on Request-only features must pass BLIS E2E <15% on majority of experiments | WP5–WP6 rework (interface extension) | Before WP5 |\n| R4 | Blackbox is beatable | Current blackbox has significant BLIS E2E error | Compute blackbox BLIS E2E baseline in WP0. If E2E mean < 12%, reassess | All WP1–WP6 wasted | Before WP1 |\n| R5 | Winning model portable to Go | Model expressible as coefficients, ONNX, or compact code | Each idea documents Go integration path during WP3 | WP5 rework | Before WP5 |\n| R6 | Lightweight Go evaluator is accurate | Research evaluator matches production behavior | Compare lightweight and production Go implementations on same inputs in WP5 | WP3 results invalid | Before WP5 merge |\n\n**Abort plans:**\n- R1 fails → derive per-request KV lengths from lifecycle data instead; may need richer feature extraction\n- R2 fails → request full-trace re-collection or apply importance weighting\n- R3 fails → propose LatencyModel interface extension (separate design doc)\n- R4 fails → cancel research; blackbox is already good enough\n- R5 fails → use ONNX runtime from Go (adds dependency)\n- R6 fails → rerun BLIS validation with production implementation; update leaderboard\n\n---\n\n## F) Architectural Evolution\n\n### Current State\n\nTwo LatencyModel backends (`sim/latency/latency.go:129-167`):\n- `hw.Roofline == true` → RooflineLatencyModel (analytical FLOPs/bandwidth)\n- `hw.Roofline == false` → BlackboxLatencyModel (2-feature regression; returns 0 for scheduling/preemption)\n\nFactory dispatch is binary. No fallback chain. No data-driven multi-method calibration.\n\n### Target State\n\nThree LatencyModel backends with ordered dispatch:\n1. `hw.Roofline == true` → RooflineLatencyModel (unchanged)\n2. StepML artifact exists at configured path → StepMLLatencyModel (new — all 5 methods data-driven)\n3. Fallback → BlackboxLatencyModel (preserved for backward compatibility)\n\nNew CLI flag `--stepml-model <path>` specifies the artifact location. When absent, falls back to blackbox.\n\n### Evolution Path\n\n1. **WP0 (lightweight):** Add `sim/latency/stepml.go` with minimal tree evaluator + coefficient loader. Registers via existing factory. Enables BLIS validation during research. Not production quality.\n2. **WP5 (production):** Replace lightweight implementation with production-quality code — proper error handling, comprehensive tests (INV-M-1 through INV-M-6), R20 degenerate input handling.\n\n### What Remains Unchanged\n\n- LatencyModel interface (frozen at `sim/latency_model.go:7-23`)\n- **RooflineLatencyModel: zero code changes.** The `--roofline` path returns before StepML dispatch.\n- All call sites (`sim/simulator.go`, `sim/event.go`, `sim/batch_formation.go`)\n- Batch formation, scheduling, routing, KV cache modules\n- Cluster-level configuration\n\n### Roofline Isolation Guarantee\n\nStepML findings for scheduling overhead, preemption, and queueing apply ONLY to the StepML LatencyModel. Not propagated to roofline because:\n1. Factory dispatch order: `hw.Roofline == true` checked first — StepML unreachable when roofline active\n2. No shared mutable state: separate artifacts and coefficients\n3. No defaults.yaml changes for roofline\n4. Verification: regression test asserting byte-identical `--roofline` stdout (INV-6)\n\n---\n\n## G) Frozen Interface Reference\n\n```go\n// sim/latency_model.go:7-23\ntype LatencyModel interface {\n    StepTime(batch []*Request) int64\n    QueueingTime(req *Request) int64\n    OutputTokenProcessingTime() int64\n    SchedulingProcessingTime() int64\n    PreemptionProcessingTime() int64\n}\n```\n\nRegistration variable (`sim/latency_model.go:31`):\n```go\nvar NewLatencyModelFunc func(coeffs LatencyCoeffs, hw ModelHardwareConfig) (LatencyModel, error)\n```\n\nFactory (`sim/latency/latency.go:129`):\n```go\nfunc NewLatencyModel(coeffs sim.LatencyCoeffs, hw sim.ModelHardwareConfig) (sim.LatencyModel, error)\n```\n\n---\n\n## H) Cross-Cutting Infrastructure Plan\n\n### H.1 Shared Test Infrastructure\n\n- **Existing:** `hypotheses/lib/harness.sh`, `hypotheses/lib/analyze_helpers.py`\n- **New (WP0):** `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` — data loader, evaluation harness, BLIS validation harness, baselines, feature extraction tools. All ideas use these.\n- **New (WP0):** `sim/latency/stepml.go` — lightweight Go tree evaluator for BLIS validation during research\n- **New (WP5):** `sim/latency/stepml_test.go` — production Go unit tests with INV-M-1 through INV-M-6\n\n### H.2 Documentation Maintenance\n\n| Trigger | Owner | What Updates |\n|---|---|---|\n| WP0 creates `hypotheses/h-stepml/` and `sim/latency/stepml.go` | WP0 | CLAUDE.md file organization + latency estimation section |\n| WP0 adds `--stepml-model` flag | WP0 | CLAUDE.md CLI flags |\n| WP5 replaces lightweight with production implementation | WP5 | CLAUDE.md latency estimation section |\n| WP6 regenerates golden dataset | WP6 | CLAUDE.md golden dataset note |\n\n### H.3 CI Pipeline Changes\n\n- **WP0:** New Go file added to `go test ./sim/latency/...`. Lightweight tests only.\n- **WP0–WP4:** Python research code not CI-gated; reproducibility via run.sh\n- **WP5:** Production Go tests + benchmarks\n- **WP6:** Golden dataset regeneration + `go test ./...` verification\n\n### H.4 Dependency Management\n\n- **Python (WP0–WP4):** `requirements.txt` in `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` with pinned versions\n- **Go (WP0):** Zero new dependencies for lightweight evaluator (pure Go tree traversal + JSON parsing)\n- **Go (WP5):** Depends on winning model. Coefficient export = zero new deps. ONNX = adds `onnxruntime-go`.\n\n### H.5 Interface Freeze Schedule\n\n- **LatencyModel interface:** Already frozen. No changes.\n- **NewLatencyModelFunc signature:** Already frozen. StepML uses existing `ModelHardwareConfig` with optional new fields.\n- **No new interfaces introduced.** StepML is a policy template.\n\n---\n\n## I) Work Package Plan\n\n### WP0: Shared Infrastructure + BLIS Validation Loop\n\n**Building Block Change:** Adds Data Pipeline + BLIS Validation Harness + lightweight StepML LatencyModel\n**Extension Type:** Subsystem module (new infrastructure) + policy template (lightweight Go evaluator)\n**Motivation:** All subsequent WPs depend on data loading, BLIS validation capability, and the blackbox E2E baseline. The BLIS validation harness is the primary evaluation tool — without it, ideas cannot measure the P1 metric.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: Data parsing (step-level + request-level + MFU benchmarks from InferSim bench_data), Python evaluation harness, Go tree evaluator, BLIS validation harness, blackbox E2E baseline, component-level error attribution, per-request KV length extraction, sampling bias characterization, prefix cache semantics (D-8)\n- Out: Any model training, any idea-specific code, production-quality Go implementation\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-0-1: Row count of parsed datasets matches source file counts\n- BC-0-2: MFU benchmark data indexed and queryable by GPU type, matrix shape, attention config\n- BC-0-3: Go tree evaluator implements all 5 LatencyModel methods and loads exported artifacts\n- BC-0-4: BLIS validation harness runs all 16 experiments and outputs E2E/TTFT/ITL mean errors\n- BC-0-5: Blackbox E2E baseline established (the number Round 2 must beat)\n- BC-0-6: Component-level error attribution identifies which of the 5 methods dominates E2E error\n- BC-0-7: Sampling bias report documents step_id uniformity, autocorrelation, per-experiment representation\n\n**Risks:**\n1. Sampling is systematically biased → characterization detects it; abort per R2\n2. Blackbox already achieves <12% E2E mean → reassess research justification per R4\n3. Go tree evaluator has accuracy issues → validated against Python predictions before WP3\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** Creates `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` and `sim/latency/stepml.go`. Updates CLAUDE.md.\n\n**Validation Gate:** R1, R2, R4 must pass before WP1.\n\n---\n\n**Implementation Guide:**\n\n**Architectural Impact:** Adds `sim/latency/stepml.go` as a third LatencyModel backend (lightweight, research-only). Adds Python infrastructure under `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/`.\n\n**Tasks (grouped by subsystem):**\n\n*Data loading and characterization:*\n1. Create directory structure and requirements.txt\n2. Implement data loader: parse step-level traces from all 20 experiments into unified Parquet\n3. Implement request-level data loader: parse per-request lifecycle metrics\n4. Index MFU benchmarks from InferSim bench_data (make queryable by GPU+shape+config)\n5. Characterize sampling distribution (bias detection per R2 gate)\n6. Verify step.duration_us semantics + resolve prefix cache semantics (D-8)\n\n*Python evaluation (diagnostics):*\n7. Implement per-step evaluation harness (MAPE, MSPE, Pearson r, p99 error, bootstrap CI)\n8. Implement per-step baselines (blackbox re-trained, roofline, naive mean)\n\n*Feature extraction tools:*\n9. Component-level error attribution tool (e2e_decomposition.py): ablate each of 5 methods to measure marginal E2E error contribution\n10. Per-request KV length extractor (lifecycle_kv_extractor.py): derive per-step kv_mean, kv_max, kv_sum from lifecycle data\n\n*BLIS validation infrastructure:*\n11. Go tree evaluator (sim/latency/stepml.go): lightweight LatencyModel loading exported artifacts, ~200 lines\n12. BLIS validation harness (validate_blis.sh): run BLIS on 16 traces, output E2E/TTFT/ITL per experiment\n13. Blackbox E2E baseline: run validation harness with current blackbox coefficients — establish the baseline\n14. Validate ProgressIndex as KV proxy (R1 gate)\n\n---\n\n### WP1: Research Ideation\n\n**Building Block Change:** Populates Experiment Engine inputs\n**Extension Type:** Process (skill invocation)\n**Motivation:** Generate 3+ literature-grounded ideas for achieving <10% BLIS E2E mean error via any combination of LatencyModel method improvements.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: Write `problem.md` from design doc (including WP0 baseline results + component error attribution), invoke `/research-ideas`\n- Out: Model training, experiment execution\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-1-1: `research.md` contains 3+ ideas with literature citations\n- BC-1-2: Each idea specifies which of the 5 LatencyModel methods it targets\n- BC-1-3: Each idea documents its Go integration path\n- BC-1-4: Ideas are diverse — not all limited to step-time-only ML models\n\n**Risks:**\n1. Ideas are too similar → problem.md explicitly requests diverse approaches (e.g., step-time ML, end-to-end calibration, multi-component optimization)\n2. Ideas ignore the non-StepTime methods → problem.md includes WP0 component error attribution showing which methods contribute most to E2E error\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** None. Produces `research.md` consumed by WP2.\n\n---\n\n### WP2: Hypothesis Scaffolding\n\n**Building Block Change:** Adds Experiment Engine structure\n**Extension Type:** Process (directory creation + HYPOTHESIS.md authoring)\n**Motivation:** Map research ideas to testable hypotheses with idea-specific sub-hypothesis decomposition.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: Extract top 3-5 ideas from research.md, create per-idea directories, write HYPOTHESIS.md files\n- Out: Experiment code, running experiments\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-2-1: Each idea has 2-3 sub-hypotheses with idea-specific decomposition (NOT fixed h1-features/h2-model/h3-generalization)\n- BC-2-2: Each HYPOTHESIS.md includes Related Work with citations from research.md\n- BC-2-3: At least one sub-hypothesis per idea reports BLIS E2E mean error\n- BC-2-4: Claims and refutation criteria expressed in terms of BLIS E2E mean error where possible\n- BC-2-5: Each idea documents its training strategy and data split approach (subject to data integrity requirements)\n\n**Risks:**\n1. Ideas don't map to hypotheses → each idea must specify a falsifiable BLIS E2E claim\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** Creates directory structure consumed by WP3.\n\n**Validation Gate:** Convergence review (h-design, 5 perspectives) on each idea's HYPOTHESIS.md.\n\n---\n\n### WP3: Wave-Parallel Experimentation\n\n**Building Block Change:** Executes Experiment Engine\n**Extension Type:** Policy template (new algorithms per idea)\n**Motivation:** Test each idea's approach and measure BLIS E2E mean error.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: All sub-hypotheses per idea, using WP0 shared infrastructure\n- Out: Production Go integration (that's WP5)\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-3-1: Every idea uses WP0's data loader (no custom parsing)\n- BC-3-2: Every idea's final sub-hypothesis reports BLIS E2E mean error via validate_blis.sh\n- BC-3-3: Every FINDINGS.md includes BLIS E2E per experiment + data integrity documentation (which data was training vs. evaluation)\n- BC-3-4: Data integrity requirements satisfied: non-overlapping splits, no feature leakage, no model selection on training experiments' BLIS E2E\n- BC-3-5: Ideas with BLIS E2E worse than blackbox baseline are dropped\n- BC-3-6: Each idea's training strategy and split documented and justified\n\n**Risks:**\n1. All ideas fail → re-examine feature assumptions; revisit R1, R3\n2. BLIS validation harness bottleneck → each BLIS run takes ~2-5 min; 16 experiments × multiple ideas is manageable\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** Consumes WP0 shared infrastructure. Each idea writes only to its own directory.\n\n**Validation Gate:** R3 evaluated after WP3. R5 confirmed for surviving ideas.\n\n---\n\n### WP4: Leaderboard & Selection\n\n**Building Block Change:** Populates Leaderboard\n**Extension Type:** Process (analysis + documentation)\n**Motivation:** Compare all ideas on BLIS E2E mean error and select the winner.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: All ideas' BLIS validation results and FINDINGS.md\n- Out: Winner selection, README.md with leaderboard\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-4-1: Rankings ordered by P1 metric (BLIS E2E mean error) first\n- BC-4-2: Data integrity verified: each idea's training/evaluation boundary documented\n- BC-4-3: Winner identified with Go integration path documented\n- BC-4-4: Falsification criteria checked (design doc section)\n\n**Risks:**\n1. No idea achieves <10% BLIS E2E → evaluate falsification criteria; consider abandoning StepML\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** Produces README.md. Inputs to WP5.\n\n---\n\n### WP5: Production Go Integration\n\n**Building Block Change:** Replaces lightweight StepML with production implementation\n**Extension Type:** Policy template (production-quality algorithm behind LatencyModel interface)\n**Motivation:** Replace WP0's lightweight Go evaluator with production-quality code.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: Winning model's artifacts and integration path from WP4\n- Out: Production BLIS validation (that's WP6)\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-5-1: StepML implements all 5 LatencyModel methods (production quality)\n- BC-5-2: Factory dispatch: roofline → stepml (if artifact) → blackbox (fallback)\n- BC-5-3: INV-M-1 through INV-M-6 all pass with comprehensive tests\n- BC-5-4: All existing tests pass (roofline and blackbox unchanged)\n- BC-5-5: CLI flag validated per R3/R10/R18\n- BC-5-6: Roofline isolation regression test — byte-identical stdout (INV-6)\n- BC-5-7: R20 degenerate inputs handled (all cases from design doc table)\n- BC-5-8: Production predictions match lightweight evaluator results on same inputs (R6 validation)\n\n**Risks:**\n1. Model too complex for Go → ONNX runtime or coefficient export\n2. Prediction latency > 1ms → simplify or approximate\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** Updates CLAUDE.md. Creates production `sim/latency/stepml.go` and `sim/latency/stepml_test.go`.\n\n---\n\n### WP6: Production Validation & Promotion\n\n**Building Block Change:** Validates StepML end-to-end; promotes to default\n**Extension Type:** Tier composition (validation over existing simulation)\n**Motivation:** Verify production Go implementation matches research results and passes Stage 2 integration gate.\n\n**Scope:**\n- In: Production StepML from WP5, standard workload scenarios\n- Out: Updated golden dataset, CLAUDE.md\n\n**Behavioral Guarantees:**\n- BC-6-1: BLIS E2E mean error < 10% on standard workloads (production Go, not lightweight evaluator)\n- BC-6-2: TTFT mean error < 15%, ITL mean error < 15%\n- BC-6-3: No P99 ranking inversions vs. blackbox\n- BC-6-4: Throughput prediction error < 15%\n- BC-6-5: Golden dataset regenerated and documented (R12)\n- BC-6-6: INV-6 determinism: two runs with same seed produce byte-identical stdout\n\n**Risks:**\n1. Production implementation diverges from lightweight evaluator → R6 gate catches this\n2. Golden dataset changes break tests → regenerate with verification\n\n**Cross-Cutting:** Updates CLAUDE.md (defaults, implementation focus). Regenerates `testdata/goldendataset.json`.\n\n---\n\n## J) Dependency DAG\n\n```\nWP0 (Shared Infrastructure + BLIS Validation Loop + Go Evaluator)\n │\n ├── R1, R2, R4 validation gates\n │\n ▼\nWP1 (Research Ideation)\n │\n ▼\nWP2 (Hypothesis Scaffolding)\n │\n ├─────────┬─────────┐\n ▼         ▼         ▼\nWP3-a    WP3-b    WP3-c    (parallel across ideas; sequential sub-hypotheses within)\n │         │         │\n └─────────┴─────────┘\n           │\n           ├── R3, R5 validation gates\n           ▼\n         WP4 (Leaderboard — ranked by BLIS E2E)\n           │\n           ▼\n         WP5 (Production Go Integration)\n           │\n           ├── R6 validation gate\n           ▼\n         WP6 (Production Validation & Promotion)\n```\n\n**Parallelizable workstreams:**\n- WP3-a, WP3-b, WP3-c are fully parallel (independent ideas, shared read-only data)\n- Within WP3-x: sub-hypotheses are sequential (idea-specific dependency chain)\n- WP5 and WP6 are strictly sequential\n\n**Merge sequencing:**\n- WP0 must complete and pass R1/R2/R4 before WP1\n- WP2 must complete before any WP3\n- All WP3 must complete before WP4\n- WP4 must confirm R3/R5 before WP5\n- WP5 must pass R6 before WP6\n\n---\n\n## K) Design Bug Prevention Checklist\n\n### General\n\n- [ ] **Scaffolding creep:** Every Python module in WP0 has tests. Go evaluator in WP0 has basic tests. No dead code.\n- [ ] **Documentation drift:** CLAUDE.md updated in WP0 (Go evaluator, shared infra), WP5 (production), WP6 (golden dataset).\n- [ ] **Test infrastructure duplication:** All experiments use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/` and `validate_blis.sh`.\n- [ ] **Golden dataset staleness:** WP6 regenerates with verification (R12).\n\n### DES-Specific\n\n- [ ] **Type catalog trap:** No Go struct definitions in this macro plan. Evolution described behaviorally.\n- [ ] **Fidelity for its own sake:** Every modeled component traces to AQ-1 (E2E mean fidelity).\n- [ ] **Golden without invariant:** WP5 includes INV-M-1 through INV-M-6 companion tests.\n- [ ] **Mixing exogenous and endogenous:** StepML is a pure query (no events, no state mutation).\n\n### Module Architecture\n\n- [ ] **Shotgun surgery:** StepML constructed in one place (factory in `sim/latency/latency.go`).\n- [ ] **Config mixing:** StepML config fields module-scoped (R16).\n- [ ] **No silent data loss (R1):** Factory fallback logged, not silent.\n- [ ] **Guard division (R11):** Zero denominators checked in prediction code.\n- [ ] **Strict YAML parsing (R10):** New fields use `yaml.KnownFields(true)`.\n- [ ] **CLI flag precedence (R18):** `--stepml-model` does not silently override defaults.yaml.\n\n### Roofline Isolation\n\n- [ ] **Roofline byte-identical output:** WP5 regression test (BC-5-6).\n- [ ] **No roofline code touched:** StepML branch after `if hw.Roofline` check.\n- [ ] **No alpha coefficient sharing:** Separate artifacts.\n- [ ] **No defaults.yaml roofline changes:** Additive StepML section only.\n\n### Data Integrity (Research-Specific)\n\n- [ ] **No data leakage:** Every idea's train/valid/test sets are strictly non-overlapping (Integrity Req #1).\n- [ ] **No evaluation on training data:** Metrics clearly labeled as training vs. validation (Integrity Req #2).\n- [ ] **BLIS E2E boundary:** Model selection/tuning not done on BLIS E2E of training experiments (Integrity Req #3).\n- [ ] **Temporal leakage awareness:** Ideas using step-level splits document their leakage prevention (Integrity Req #4).\n- [ ] **Feature leakage:** No post-execution features used as inputs (Integrity Req #5).\n- [ ] **Reproducibility:** Seeds fixed, splits saved, dependencies pinned (Integrity Req #6).\n","numLines":616,"startLine":1,"totalLines":616}}}
