{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01LzoCuddnYCJWeY913xds3r","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# FINDINGS: H5 — Leave-One-Model-Out (LOMO) for CMA-ES\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-28\n     4→**Status:** SUPPORTED\n     5→\n     6→## Claim\n     7→\n     8→CMA-ES-optimized coefficients from one model group, when applied to another model group's experiments, achieve <50% E2E error — demonstrating partial cross-model transfer.\n     9→\n    10→## Result\n    11→\n    12→**Mean best-donor LOMO E2E: 14.8%** (threshold <50%). All 4 model groups have a donor achieving <25% E2E. **Strongly supported.**\n    13→\n    14→## Cross-Model Transfer Matrix (E2E %)\n    15→\n    16→| Donor → Target | codellama-34b | llama-2-70b | llama-2-7b | mixtral-8x7b |\n    17→|---|---|---|---|---|\n    18→| **codellama-34b** | — | 21.2% | 24.3% | 21.2% |\n    19→| **llama-2-70b** | 24.7% | — | 94.0% | **5.1%** |\n    20→| **llama-2-7b** | 40.4% | 53.8% | — | 53.8% |\n    21→| **mixtral-8x7b** | **11.9%** | 26.0% | **20.9%** | — |\n    22→\n    23→## Best Donor Per Target\n    24→\n    25→| Target Model | Best Donor | LOMO E2E | In-Dist E2E | Degradation |\n    26→|---|---|---|---|---|\n    27→| codellama-34b | mixtral-8x7b | **11.9%** | 7.9% | +4.0pp |\n    28→| llama-2-70b | codellama-34b | **21.2%** | 8.3% | +12.9pp |\n    29→| llama-2-7b | mixtral-8x7b | **20.9%** | 22.2% | -1.3pp |\n    30→| mixtral-8x7b | llama-2-70b | **5.1%** | 25.9% | -20.8pp |\n    31→\n    32→## Key Findings\n    33→\n    34→1. **Cross-model transfer is remarkably good.** Mean best-donor LOMO E2E of 14.8% vs in-distribution mean of 15.1%. For 2/4 targets (7b, mixtral), the cross-model artifact actually performs BETTER than the in-distribution one.\n    35→\n    36→2. **70B → Mixtral is the best transfer pair (5.1% E2E).** The llama-2-70b CMA-ES artifact applied to Mixtral produces 5.1% E2E — better than Mixtral's own in-distribution 25.9%. This suggests llama-2-70b's overhead floor and scheduling coefficients are closer to Mixtral's optimal values than Mixtral's own CMA-ES found.\n    37→\n    38→3. **Mixtral is the best universal donor.** Mixtral's artifact transfers to codellama-34b (11.9%), llama-2-7b (20.9%), and llama-2-70b (26.0%) — all under 27%. This may be because Mixtral's higher overhead (9,125us) creates a more conservative simulation that generalizes.\n    39→\n    40→4. **7B artifacts are the worst donors.** llama-2-7b's artifact produces 40-54% E2E on all targets — the weakest transfer. This is expected: 7B has the smallest overhead floor (3,897us → optimized to 5,051us), which is too fast for larger models.\n    41→\n    42→5. **Codellama-34b is a strong universal donor.** Consistent 21-24% across all targets — suggesting TP=2 step dynamics are a reasonable middle ground.\n    43→\n    44→## Comparison with Prior Rounds\n    45→\n    46→| Round | LOMO Metric | Result | Approach |\n    47→|---|---|---|---|\n    48→| R1 | Per-step MAPE | 2,559.7% | Per-experiment XGBoost |\n    49→| R2 | Per-step MAPE | 108.6% | Regime ensemble |\n    50→| R3 Idea 2 | Per-step MAPE | 2,281.6% | FairBatching 3-coeff OLS |\n    51→| **R3 Idea 3** | **E2E error** | **14.8%** | **CMA-ES artifact transfer** |\n    52→\n    53→CMA-ES artifacts have dramatically better cross-model transfer than per-step models because they capture simulation-level dynamics (overhead floor calibration, scheduling overhead) that are partially model-independent.\n    54→\n    55→## Refutation Assessment\n    56→\n    57→- **SUPPORTED:** 14.8% << 50% threshold\n    58→- CMA-ES captures transferable simulation dynamics, not just model-specific step times\n    59→- Practical implication: for a new model without ground-truth data, applying the Mixtral or codellama-34b CMA-ES artifact provides a reasonable starting point (~12-24% E2E)\n    60→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01YDgwzYnaKyFjGGak7aDXLb","session_id":"c72182bb-90d4-4f72-be1e-6f3d8138bce2","uuid":"7ee3879c-f65b-4496-bede-b7e9a8d92260"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JVhhm6Dxq8qcGoVsfNHkwm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# FINDINGS: H4 — Leave-One-Workload-Out (LOWO) for CMA-ES\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-28\n     4→**Status:** PARTIALLY SUPPORTED\n     5→\n     6→## Claim\n     7→\n     8→CMA-ES-optimized coefficients, when broken down per workload, achieve consistent accuracy without systematic overfitting to any single workload. All workloads within 2x of aggregate E2E.\n     9→\n    10→## Result (Part A: Per-Workload Breakdown)\n    11→\n    12→**Aggregate E2E: 15.1%**. Not all workloads within 2x — mixtral-roleplay (34.2%) exceeds 2 × 15.1% = 30.2%.\n    13→\n    14→## Per-Model x Per-Workload E2E Error\n    15→\n    16→| Model Group | Codegen | General | Roleplay | Range (pp) | Mean |\n    17→|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n    18→| llama-2-7b | — | — | 22.2% | — | 22.2% |\n    19→| llama-2-70b | **3.8%** | 16.2% | **6.9%** | 12.4 | 9.0% |\n    20→| codellama-34b | **5.0%** | **1.2%** | 17.5% | 16.3 | 7.9% |\n    21→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 30.9% | 12.7% | 34.2% | 21.5 | 25.9% |\n    22→\n    23→## Key Findings\n    24→\n    25→1. **Dense models generalize well across workloads.** llama-2-70b (9.0% mean, 12.4pp range) and codellama-34b (7.9% mean, 16.3pp range) show stable E2E across all 3 workloads. CMA-ES captures model-intrinsic properties.\n    26→\n    27→2. **Mixtral has highest workload variance.** 21.5pp range, with codegen (30.9%) and roleplay (34.2%) much worse than general (12.7%). The MoE architecture's step-time depends more on workload-specific batch composition.\n    28→\n    29→3. **Roleplay is the hardest workload for 3/4 models.** llama-2-7b (22.2%), codellama-34b (17.5%), mixtral (34.2%) all show worst performance on roleplay. This may be related to roleplay's shorter, more variable output lengths creating more diverse batch compositions.\n    30→\n    31→4. **General workload is most predictable.** 3/4 model groups have their best or near-best E2E on general (codellama 1.2%, mixtral 12.7%, 70b 16.2%).\n    32→\n    33→## TTFT and ITL Breakdown\n    34→\n    35→| Experiment | E2E | TTFT | ITL |\n    36→|---|---|---|---|\n    37→| llama-2-7b-roleplay | 22.2% | 60.8% | 91.1% |\n    38→| llama-2-70b-general | 16.2% | 82.5% | 72.0% |\n    39→| llama-2-70b-hf-codegen | 3.8% | 67.6% | 111.6% |\n    40→| llama-2-70b-roleplay | 6.9% | 67.6% | 117.0% |\n    41→| mixtral-codegen | 30.9% | 66.4% | 41.5% |\n    42→| mixtral-general | 12.7% | 57.3% | 78.1% |\n    43→| mixtral-roleplay | 34.2% | 69.3% | 34.5% |\n    44→| codellama-34b-general | 1.2% | 69.3% | 102.7% |\n    45→| codellama-34b-codegen | 5.0% | 68.9% | 90.2% |\n    46→| codellama-34b-roleplay | 17.5% | 66.2% | 135.4% |\n    47→\n    48→## Refutation Assessment\n    49→\n    50→- **Part A: PARTIALLY SUPPORTED** — 8/10 experiments within 2x aggregate, but mixtral-codegen (30.9%) and mixtral-roleplay (34.2%) exceed the 30.2% threshold\n    51→- **Part B: NOT TESTED** — would require 9 additional CMA-ES optimization runs (~4.5 hours), deferred\n    52→- Dense models demonstrate excellent workload generalization; MoE models do not\n    53→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01YDgwzYnaKyFjGGak7aDXLb","session_id":"c72182bb-90d4-4f72-be1e-6f3d8138bce2","uuid":"d1d55b8b-81aa-4abf-a155-eda25761d548"}
